<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-108-243 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 970 058</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE: Work-Group Computing Report  July 8 1991 v2 n59 p16(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Encore andamp; IBM to re-bid NASA mainframe contract. (Encore ComputerCorp.)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Encore Computer Corp. (Contracts)International Business Machines Corp. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    IBM; ENCC.andO;Topic:     Government ContractsGovernment AgencyCompetitive BiddingMicrocomputersContract Protests.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Encore Computer Corp. has received notification from NASA that the Agency iswithdrawing its initial selection of International Business Machines (IBM)for award of the Operations Automatic Data Processing (OADP) computerrequirements contract.andM;NASA had previously announced its selection of IBM for this award based onthe Best and Final Offers (BAFO's) submitted in March of this year.andP;  On June3 Encore lodged a bid protest out of which came NASA's call for re-BAFO.andM;By insuring this continued competition between Encore and IBM for the awardof one of the Government's largest ever mainframe contracts, NASA is seekingthe lowest life cycle price for mainframe class systems.andM;The re-BAFO will be limited solely to price; IBM and Encore, the twofinalists, were found to be compliant with all aspects of the solicitationincluding the demanding technical and performance requirements.andM;&quot;Our company's strategy and our NASA bid is in line with the industry trendof UNIX and microprocessor based systems to replace traditional mainframes,&quot;stated Kenneth G. Fisher, Encore chairman and chief executive officer.andM;&quot;It is to NASA's credit that the Agency is requesting a re-BAFO to assuretheir selection provides leading edge technology at a substantial savings tothe American taxpayers.&quot;andM;Over the life of the contract, this re-BAFO is expected to be hundreds ofmillions of dollars less than the $450 million original purchasing authorityestimate.andO;</TEXT></DOC>